Problem Overview

In New South Wales, road traffic accidents represent a serious public safety issue. Each year, numerous injuries and fatalities occur, resulting in significant economic losses. Although the government has invested substantial funds in road safety, such as the $2.8 billion committed over the next four years, accidents continue to occur frequently with varying degrees of severity. Sydneys traffic risks are particularly pronounced due to rapid population growth, traffic congestion, and the complexity of its road system. While many studies have focused on reducing the frequency of accidents, less research has examined the factors influencing accident severity. Therefore, this project aims to explore these contributing factors to provide new insights into how road injuries can be effectively reduced.

The goal of this project is to develop a machine learning model that predicts accident severity using historical crash data and traffic enforcement information. Framed as a multi-class classification problem, the model aims to categorise accidents into five levels of severity: fatal, serious injury, moderate injury, minor injury, and no injury. The model incorporates features such as the time and date of the incident, weather conditions, road type, number of vehicles involved, and distance from speed cameras.

The three primary objectives of this study are to:

  1. Investigate the relationship between various factors and accident severity
  2. Analyse the impact of vehicle type and the number of vehicles involved on accident outcomes
  3. Examine the role of traffic enforcement measures, such as proximity to speed cameras, in determining accident severity

By predicting accident severity, this study aims to enhance public safety and support government decision-making regarding road planning, traffic enforcement, and resource allocation.

Data Description

This study uses two datasets from the NSW Government Transport Open Data Hub to analyse factors influencing traffic accident severity across New South Wales between 2019 and 2023. Together, they capture information on crash characteristics and speed enforcement camera locations, enabling examination of environmental, temporal, and enforcement-related influences on crash outcomes.

The primary dataset, nsw_road_crash_data_20192023_crash.xlsx, contains 93,492 observations and 50 variables describing each crash. The key variable, Degree of Crash Detailed, classifies severity into five categories: Non-casualty (towaway), Minor/Other Injury, Moderate Injury, Serious Injury, and Fatal. The dataset also includes crash time, date, location, weather, road type, and vehicle involvement details. These provide a diverse mix of numerical and categorical features for predictive modelling.

The secondary dataset, nsw-speed-cameras-gps-locations-november-2021.xlsx, documents the positions of fixed and red-light speed cameras across NSW. The fixed camera sheet covers 103 roads, while the red-light camera sheet covers 201 roads, each including suburb, road name, camera count, and GPS coordinates. Both sheets were merged into a single dataframe, with each camera represented as a distinct record.

To align the datasets, crashes before November 2019 were removed, as installation dates for cameras were unavailable. Each crash was geocoded, and the distance (in km) to the nearest fixed and red-light camera was calculated using spatial analysis (WGS84 system, sf library). These distances were then added as new features to the crash dataset.

Overall pre-processing included creating new variables for camera distance, turning categorical variables into factors, and selecting columns. The code snippets are commented for ease of reading. Additionally, individual models had their own pre-processing.

# Combine the camera datasets together into 1 dataframe
# Columns to standardise
latlong_cols <- c("Lat(1)", "Long(1)", "Lat(2)", "Long(2)", "Lat(3)", "Long(3)")

# redlight cameras start with more columns than fixed cameras
redlight_cameras <- redlight_cameras %>%
  mutate(Camera_type = "Red_Light") %>%
  # Force all Lat/Long columns to numeric
  mutate(across(all_of(latlong_cols), ~ parse_number(as.character(.))))

# Add the missing columns as numeric NAs, then set Camera_type
fixed_cameras <- fixed_cameras %>%
  mutate(
    `Lat(2)`  = NA_real_,

  ) %>%
  # Ensure all Lat/Long columns exist and are numeric

speed_cam_pts <- speed_cameras %>%

# Helper to compute nearest distance (km) to a given camera set, returning a vector
nearest_km_to <- function(crash_pts, cam_pts) {
  if (nrow(cam_pts) == 0) return(rep(NA_real_, nrow(crash_pts)))
  nn_idx <- st_nearest_feature(crash_pts, cam_pts)
  as.numeric(st_distance(crash_pts, cam_pts[nn_idx, ], by_element = TRUE)) / 1000
}

# Distances
nearest_fixed_km    <- nearest_km_to(crash_sf, fixed_sf)
nearest_redlight_km <- nearest_km_to(crash_sf, redlight_sf)

# Write back to the full crash dataframe
crash_df$nearest_fixed_km    <- NA_real_
crash_df$nearest_redlight_km <- NA_real_

crash_df$nearest_fixed_km[valid_rows]    <- nearest_fixed_km
crash_df$nearest_redlight_km[valid_rows] <- nearest_redlight_km

crash_2019_2023_filtered <- crash_df

# Making a function to easily create nice looking tables from columns
style_column <- function(column,name,na="no"){
  df <- table(column,useNA=na) %>% addmargins() %>% as.matrix() %>% t() %>% as.data.frame()
  df <- cbind(c("Crash Frequency"),df)
  names(df)[1] = name
  names(df)[ncol(df)] = "Total"
  df %>% 
  kable(format = "html", booktabs = TRUE, align = "c") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, position = "center", bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive")) # Responsive allows the table to properly scale with browser size - for example, on phones.
}

Numerical Data

The dataset contains 16 numerical variables, though several serve specific purposes: Crash ID is a unique identifier, RUM and DCA codes map to categorical data, and Latitude/Longitude are used for distance calculations. The key numeric features analysed are:

Key Findings:

Temporal patterns: The dataset spans 2019-2023 (76,199 total crashes), with 2019 having only 3,132 crashes due to starting in November. Crashes show bimodal daily peaks during commute hours (8am, 4pm) and higher frequency on weekdays versus weekends.

Road characteristics: Most crashes occur on main roads (Route category analysis based on Classified Roads Schedule [4]). Speed limits of 50-60 km/h show highest crash frequency, but fatal crashes are proportionately higher at speeds >80 km/h. Most crashes involve 1-2 traffic units, with a maximum of 26 observed.

Injury counts: Number killed, seriously injured, moderately injured, and minor/other injured are all highly positively skewed discrete variables. Most crashes result in no fatalities.

Speed Limits: Crashes are recorded most frequently at 50-60km/h, likely due to these being the most common urban speed limits. However, proportionately more fatal crashes appear to occur on roads with speed limits above 80 km/h. This also appears to be the case at lower speeds of 10-20 km/h, although the lack of data here makes this extremely variable.

Speed Enforcement: nearest_fixed_km and nearest_redlight_km measure crash proximity to speed cameras (ranges: 0-979 km and 0-934 km; medians: 4.5 km and 3.1 km). Both show severe right skewness with most crashes clustered near cameras (>50,000 at 0 km in histograms). A log transformation was used to normalise the distributions for improved model performance. These variables have a high correlation, so multicollinearity is a consideration.

EDA Key Findings:

Temporal: Serious/fatal crashes peak late night (10PM-2AM); April/August/October show highest severe proportions; active school zones show reduced severity.

Weather/Environment: Most crashes in fine/daylight conditions, but poor conditions increase fatality risk; areas without street lighting show higher severe crash rates.

Road characteristics: Straight roads dominate; crashes on sealed, dry roads most common; urbanisation and road alignment affect severity.

Traffic controls: Give-way signs and roundabouts frequent; signal operation impacts outcomes.

Vehicle involvement: Rear-end collisions most common; head-on most fatal; motorcycles/pedal cycles highest risk (>50% serious/fatal); passenger cars most frequent but lower severity.

# Keep the top 10 values, group the rest to "Other"
lump_top_n <- function(x, n = 10, other_level = "Other") {
  # Tabulate frequencies
  freq <- sort(table(x), decreasing = TRUE)
  top_levels <- names(freq)[seq_len(min(n, length(freq)))]
  
  # Replace non-top with "Other"
  x_new <- ifelse(x %in% top_levels, as.character(x), other_level)
  
  factor(x_new, levels = c(top_levels, other_level))
}

Feature Engineering

As mentioned previously, we applied a log transformation to the nearest_fixed_km and nearest_redlight_km variables to normalise the distributions. Furthermore, we converted the numeric Route no. variable into the categorical and more meaningful RouteCategory variable. In addition, we converted all temporal variables (hour, day and month of crash) to cyclical values to preserve the periodicity of the variables and improve performance compared to one-hot or dummy encoding. Finally, we converted any missing values of Other TU type to None, as the missing values indicate that there was no other traffic unit involved in the crash.

## Converting temporal variables to cyclical values
crash_data_SVC <- crash_data %>%
  
  # --- Two-hour intervals ---
  mutate(
    hour_num = case_when(
      `Two-hour intervals` == "00:01 - 01:59" ~ 1,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "02:00 - 03:59" ~ 3,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "04:00 - 05:59" ~ 5,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "06:00 - 07:59" ~ 7,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "08:00 - 09:59" ~ 9,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "10:00 - 11:59" ~ 11,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "12:00 - 13:59" ~ 13,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "14:00 - 15:59" ~ 15,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "16:00 - 17:59" ~ 17,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "18:00 - 19:59" ~ 19,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "20:00 - 21:59" ~ 21,
      `Two-hour intervals` == "22:00 - 23:59" ~ 23,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    hour_sin = sin(2 * pi * hour_num / 24),
    hour_cos = cos(2 * pi * hour_num / 24)
  ) %>%
  
  # --- Day of week of crash ---
  mutate(
    day_num = case_when(
      `Day of week of crash` == "Monday"    ~ 1,
      `Day of week of crash` == "Tuesday"   ~ 2,
      `Day of week of crash` == "Wednesday" ~ 3,
      `Day of week of crash` == "Thursday"  ~ 4,
      `Day of week of crash` == "Friday"    ~ 5,
      `Day of week of crash` == "Saturday"  ~ 6,
      `Day of week of crash` == "Sunday"    ~ 7,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    day_sin = sin(2 * pi * day_num / 7),
    day_cos = cos(2 * pi * day_num / 7)
  ) %>%
  
  # --- Month of crash ---
  mutate(
    month_num = case_when(
      `Month of crash` == "January"   ~ 1,
      `Month of crash` == "February"  ~ 2,
      `Month of crash` == "March"     ~ 3,
      `Month of crash` == "April"     ~ 4,
      `Month of crash` == "May"       ~ 5,
      `Month of crash` == "June"      ~ 6,
      `Month of crash` == "July"      ~ 7,
      `Month of crash` == "August"    ~ 8,
      `Month of crash` == "September" ~ 9,
      `Month of crash` == "October"   ~ 10,
      `Month of crash` == "November"  ~ 11,
      `Month of crash` == "December"  ~ 12,
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    ),
    month_sin = sin(2 * pi * month_num / 12),
    month_cos = cos(2 * pi * month_num / 12)
  ) %>%
  
  # --- Remove temporary numeric columns ---
  dplyr::select(-hour_num, -day_num, -month_num)

crash_data_SVC <- crash_data_SVC %>%
  dplyr::mutate(`Other TU type` = `Other TU type` |> 
                  trimws() |>
                  dplyr::na_if("") |>               # empty string -> NA
                  dplyr::na_if("NA") |>             # literal "NA" -> NA
                  tidyr::replace_na("None"))        # NA -> "None"

Modelling

We implement five possible classification models, each with pros and cons, using different features. In addition to the previously discussed data cleaning and feature engineering, individual models implemented specific further cleaning methods, outlined further in the appropriate sections. Our first model, multinomial logistic regression, acts as a parametric, interpretable measure with low variability, allowing us to evaluate findings with real-world applicability.

Next, a kNN classifier is a strong non-parametric option, good at capturing local non-linearity. We would like to keep any features used low-noise, well-scaled, and keep dimensionality low. As such, we would use the same adjusted time/day features, the school zone feature, numeric speed, number of TUs, and one-hotted Urbanisation and road surface/condition features. These are then standardised, and hyperparameter k tuned with 5-fold cross-validation.

Another non-parametric option is a Support Vector Machine, strong on complex boundaries, can capture non-linearity, and supports class weights. This includes KNNs numeric features, along with dummy coding for road type variables and key interactions like Speed Urbanisation, Hour Lighting, Camera distance Speed. We implement multiple kernel types for optimal modelling.

Furthermore, we will use a random forest model. This is an effective low-bias choice as it learns non-linearity and interactions automatically and is good for categorical data (a large proportion of our features). No scaling is necessary, and it offers feature importance scores, which allows for simple real-world policy suggestions. We use time/day as adjusted previously, school zone, all weather and environment variables, all road variables, all speed variables (ordered), and can use both camera variables (as random forest is robust to multicollinearity).

Finally, LDA is a fast, stable linear comparator, strong when class-conditional distributions are near-Gaussian with shared covariance. We use the same features as above, although we implement dimensionality reduction and covariance shrinkage with FAMD to improve the model.

To evaluate the models, we will focus on macro F1 score and Balanced Accuracy. These metrics will provide a balance between ensuring that our dataset appropriately classifies even minority classes, as well as ensuring that it still reflects the data more broadly. F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall, while Balanced Accuracy is the average of recall and specificity.

In all models except for the LDA, we create a Tidymodels recipe. This allows us to perform various steps on the train and test datasets without the risk of data leakage. The recipes will be visible in the code blocks, with explanation.

Support Vector Machine

First, we need to clean the data as per the modelling plan above. The details are visible in the code. We cyclically encode the time variables, create a training and test split, and a smaller split to allow for faster training. Finally, we create the Tidymodels recipe. The individual steps are visible in the code and commented to assist with interpretation, but the main steps are imputation of missing data, dummy encoding of categorical variables, removal of highly correlated variables, downsampling to assist with the class imbalance (only in the training data), and normalisation to ensure that high-variance features do not overpower others (essential especially for SVM). In all cases, hyperparameter tuning was conducted, the results of which can be seen by expanding the section.

# Train/Test split
set.seed(5003)

## using rsample (it's what they use in tidymodels documentation)
crash_split <- initial_split(crash_data_SVC, prop = 0.65, strata = `Degree of crash - detailed`)
crash.train <- training(crash_split) # 49526 rows
crash.test  <- testing(crash_split) # 26671 rows
crash_subset <- initial_split(crash.train, prop = 0.3, strata = `Degree of crash - detailed`) # Using very few rows
crash.train.subset <- training(crash_subset) # 14855 rows

# Recipe

crash_recipe <- recipe(`Degree of crash - detailed` ~ ., data = crash.train) %>%
  update_role(`Crash ID`, new_role = "ID") %>%
  
  # Remove year of crash (we want our model to generalise across years), town (too specific, leads to overfitting for SVM), DCA (derived from RUM, redundant information), DCA supplement, sin variables
  step_rm(`Year of crash`, `Town`, `RUM - code`, `DCA - description`, `DCA supplement`, hour_sin, day_sin, month_sin) %>%
  
  # Remove the variables detailing the number of people killed/injured - these wouldn't be known until after the crash.
  step_rm(`No. killed`, `No. seriously injured`, `No. moderately injured`, `No. minor-other injured`) %>%
  
  # Removing original variables that have since been cyclically encoded
  step_rm(`Month of crash`, `Day of week of crash`, `Two-hour intervals`) %>%
  
  # Reduce high-cardinality categoricals
  step_other(all_nominal_predictors(), threshold = 0.01) %>%
  
  # Handle missing values for numeric predictors (impute with median)
  step_impute_median(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% # All remaining missing data is MAR or MCAR.
  
  # Handle missing values for categorical predictors (impute with mode)
  step_impute_mode(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  
  # Handle values that appear in CV test folds but not training folds
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors(), new_level = "unseen") %>%
  
  # Create dummy variables for all categorical predictors, since SVM requires numeric inputs
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = FALSE) %>% # Dummy coding instead of one-hot, more efficient for SVM
  
  # Remove zero-variance predictors (constant columns)
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% # Removes all columns that only have a single value (e.g., 0), since they cannot help the model
  
  # Feature Selection: Removing highly correlated features - done after creating dummy variables.
  step_corr(all_numeric_predictors(), threshold = 0.95) %>%
  
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% # Apparently step_corr can create zero-variance features, so this removes them?
  
  # Because we have severely imbalanced classes
  themis::step_downsample(`Degree of crash - detailed`, under_ratio = 1.5, seed = 5003, skip = TRUE) %>%
  
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>%
  
  # Normalize/scale all numeric predictors
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  
  # Just a safety net
  step_zv(all_predictors())

For the most interpretable result, we will start with a linear SVM. This will give us a hyperplane that we can directly interpret the feature weights of. We will tune the cost hyperparameter with 5-fold cross-validation. This determines the penalty applied to points falling on the wrong side of the hyperplane. A higher penalty typically leads to a model that more closely fits the training data, but risks overfitting (higher variance, lower bias).

Although the balanced accuracy is relatively high (64.2%), the macro F1 score (0.361) is quite low. It is possible that by mapping our data to a higher dimensional space, we can then classify data that was not previously linearly separable by the linear hyperplane of our first SVM and thus achieve better performance. We will begin this process with a polynomial SVM.

We tried multiple degrees of polynomial and determined that degree 4 performed the best overall, although with marginal performance differences. The code for degree 2 and degree 6 are available in the appendices. Hyperparameter tuning was conducted with 5-fold cross-validation to obtain the best pair of hyperparameters.

KNN

Our next model is a k-Nearest Neighbours model. The hyperparameter to tune here is k, the number of neighbours. Smaller values will increase the bias while increasing the variance, while larger values will do the opposite. The pre-processing is similar to the SVM models, but with more of a focus on reducing dimensionality, as KNN models perform poorly in high dimensions due to the curse of dimensionality (i.e., distances between data points in the high-dimensional space become large). The workflow is included in the following code, with comments for elaboration.

# Selecting specific features for knn, as it struggles in high dimensions.
selected_features <- c(
  # Temporal after cyclical encoding
  "month_sin",
  "day_sin", 
  "hour_sin",

  "Urbanisation",
  "Weather",
  "Natural lighting",
  "Street lighting",

  "nearest_fixed_km",
  "nearest_redlight_km",
  
  # Impact characteristics
  "First impact type",
  "DCA - description",
  "Key TU type",
  "Other TU type",
  
  # Target
  "Degree of crash - detailed"
)

  "School zone location", "School zone active",

)

  step_impute_median(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% # All remaining missing data is MAR or MCAR.
  
  # Handle missing values for categorical predictors (impute with mode)
  step_impute_mode(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  
  # Handle values that appear in CV test folds but not training folds
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors(), new_level = "unseen") %>%
  
  # Create dummy variables for all categorical predictors, since SVM requires numeric inputs

Given the large number of categorical features in our model, dummy coding inflates the number of variables substantially. As such, the diminished performance is expected: KNN struggles to create accurate clusters in high-dimensional spaces. Our next model, random forest, is quite different, able to naturally handle categorical variables without separate encoding.

Random Forest

The random forest model was selected because it can simultaneously handle both numerical and categorical features while capturing non-linear relationships between variables. It involves generating multiple decision trees,each trained on a randomised subset of data and features. During the prediction process,each tree casts an independent vote and the final outcome is determined by majority vote. This can effectively reduce overfitting compared to basic decision trees, and enhance overall performance.

As such, the pre-processing required was much simpler: Removing irrelevant or data leaking variables, converting categorical variables to factors, imputing missing data with median/mode, and downsampling.

set.seed(5003)
# RF is more robust - just need to handle missing values, make sure variables are factors, remove any identifiers, and deal with class imbalance
rf_recipe <- recipe(`Degree of crash - detailed` ~ ., data = crash.train) %>%
  update_role(`Crash ID`, new_role = "ID") %>%
  
  # Remove variables (see SVM code)
  step_rm(`Year of crash`, `Town`, `RUM - code`, `DCA - description`, `DCA supplement`, hour_sin, day_sin, month_sin, `No. killed`, `No. seriously injured`, `No. moderately injured`, `No. minor-other injured`, `Month of crash`, `Day of week of crash`, `Two-hour intervals`) %>%
  # The rest
  step_string2factor(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_impute_median(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_impute_mode(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  themis::step_downsample(`Degree of crash - detailed`, under_ratio = 1.5, seed = 5003, skip = TRUE) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors())

Multinomial Logistic Regression

Logistic Regression is a supervised learning algorithm widely used for classification problems. It calculates the probability that an observation belongs to a particular class through a logistic (sigmoid) function applied to a linear combination of predictors. In this study, the model is used to predict crash severity levelsNon-casualty, Minor Injury, Moderate Injury, Serious Injury, and Fatalbased on environmental, temporal, vehicular, and enforcement-related factors.

Because the outcome variable is categorical with ordered severity levels, a multinomial logistic regression was applied. This approach estimates the probability of each crash belonging to one of several severity categories by modelling the log-odds of outcomes as a function of the predictors. A key benefit of logistic regression is that it provides interpretable coefficients showing how each factor influences the likelihood of more severe crashes, making it ideal for policy and safety applications where transparency and explainability are important. The pre-processing is extremely similar to what has been done previously, with the key difference being that we used one-hot encoding rather than dummy coding of categorical variables as this enables better performance with the engine used. The below code is commented to explain the process of pre-processing, model creation, and training.

set.seed(5003)

crash_model_data_LR <- crash_data_SVC %>%

lr_data <- crash_model_data_LR %>%
  dplyr::select(dplyr::all_of(selected_vars), `Degree of crash - detailed`)

lr.train <- training(lr_split) # 49526 obs
lr.test  <- testing(lr_split) # 26671 obs

lr_recipe <- recipe(`Degree of crash - detailed` ~ ., data = lr.train) %>%
  # Handle missing values for numeric predictors (impute with median)
  step_impute_median(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% # All remaining missing data is MAR or MCAR.
  # Handle missing values for categorical predictors (impute with mode)
  step_unknown(all_nominal_predictors(), new_level = "unknown") %>%
  
  # Handle values that appear in CV test folds but not training folds
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors(), new_level = "unseen") %>%
  # Reduce high-cardinality categoricals
  step_other(all_nominal_predictors(), threshold = 0.01) %>%
  
  # Create dummy variables for all categorical predictors
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = TRUE) %>% # One-hot better for glmnet
  
  # Because we have severely imbalanced classes
  themis::step_downsample(`Degree of crash - detailed`, under_ratio = 1.5, seed = 5003, skip = TRUE) %>% # Can change skip = FALSE once hyperparameter tuning is complete to create a balanced model.
  
  step_lincomb(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors())

# Multinomial logistic regression with tunable penalty
multinom_spec <- multinom_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("glmnet", standardize = TRUE) %>%
  set_mode("classification")

# Create workflow
log_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(lr_recipe) %>%
  add_model(multinom_spec)

# Cross-validation with stratification
crash_folds <- vfold_cv(lr.train, v = 5, strata = `Degree of crash - detailed`)

# Tune - grid for penalty parameter
multinom_grid <- crossing(penalty = 10^c(-3,-2,-1),
                          mixture = seq(0, 1, by = 0.5))

lf_res <- log_wf %>%
  tune_grid(
    resamples = crash_folds,
    grid = multinom_grid,
    metrics = metric_set(f_meas, bal_accuracy),
    control = control_grid(
      verbose = FALSE
    )
  )

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

We approached LDA in a distinct way to the other models. We assumed that LDA would perform poorly, as it relies on an assumption of normality that categorical predictors do not tend to follow. As such, we implemented Factor Analysis of Mixed Information (FAMD), a combination of Principal Components Analysis (PCA) and Multiple Correspondence Analysis (MCA) that allows for dimensionality reduction. We hoped that this change would allow LDA to perform better, while maintaining interpretability. The data cleaning and FAMD prediction process is visible below.

Click to see details

The top variables contributing to the first two FAMD dimensions (below) were First impact type, DCA description, RUM description, and Other traffic unit type, each contributing approximately 1516% to the variance explained. These variables collectively describe the mechanics and nature of the crash event, indicating that collision configuration and the types of units involved were the dominant factors structuring the data. Secondary contributors included Local Government Area (LGA), Urbanisation, Number of traffic units involved, and proximity to traffic signals or red lights, reflecting spatial and environmental influences. Variables such as Speed limit, Street lighting, and Alignment contributed to a lesser extent but nonetheless captured contextual aspects of road design and visibility conditions.

This pattern likely reflects the limited separability of the classes in the reduced-dimensional space and the inherent assumption of multivariate normality, which may not hold for datasets comprising both categorical and continuous variables.

Performance Evaluation

The summary table of best hyperparameters, along with F1 score and Balanced Accuracy on the test sample, are included below. Hyperparameters were optimised for balanced accuracy, although models tended not to perform significantly differently when optimised for F1 score. Comments are included, comparing each model.

Summary of Results and Hyperparameters for Each Model
Details Linear_SVM Poly_4_SVM Radial_SVM KNN RF Logistic_Regression LDA
Hyperparameters C: 1 C: 1, Scale: 4 C: 10, Sigma: 0.001 K: 25 Trees: 1000, Min Node Size: 20, Predictors per Split: 4 Penalty: 0.01, Elastic Net Mixture: 0.5 N/A
F1 Score 0.361 0.371 0.371 0.298 0.374 0.371 0.252
Balanced Accuracy 0.642 0.637 0.635 0.576 0.642 0.644 0.576
Comments Good performance, interpretable variable weightings from hyperplane. Slightly improved F1 score but worsened balanced accuracy. Limited change from polynomial kernel, struggles with minority class. Poor performance, likely due to curse of dimensionality. Good non-parametric performance. Likely more room for improvement with further hyperparameter tuning, although limited due to computational restrictions. Best parametric model, interpretable feature weights. Penalty term assists in simple feature selection. Poor performance due to categorical nature of dataset. Unable to linearly separate classes even with feature engineering and selection.

Overall, the best performing model by balanced accuracy was logistic regression (64.4%), while by F1 score it was the Random Forest model (0.374). However, most models achieved around 64% balanced accuracy, with only the KNN and LDA models performing more poorly. Minor tweaks (e.g., using log1p transformations instead of simple log transformation) lead to minor changes in performance, but with overall consistent trends.

The interpretability of models is also a consideration: Linear SVM, multinomial logistic regression and random forest all provide easy access to feature weights or relevance scores, allowing us to determine which factors may be more or less relevant. Additionally, looking at the top factors in the FAMD features provides us similar insight.

Conclusion

Although no one model performed well enough for deployment, we observed that the most frequent confusion of our models was between semantically similar classes (i.e., Non-casualty vs Minor injury; Moderate vs Serious Injury). This suggests that models are making some progress towards accurately classifying the crashes, and are simply limited at a more nuanced level.

The exception to this, notably, is the Fatal class. Despite undersampling while training to bring the majority classes down to a ratio of 1.5:1 to the Fatal class, the models still struggled to accurately classify these crashes. When fatal accidents did occur, the models were generally most likely to classify them as Fatal, but all models were prone to predicting Fatal for crashes that resulted in moderate or serious injury, but no fatality. Future research should consider a more in-depth handling of fatal crashes in the data, such as by using custom decision thresholds (as suggested by Adkins, 2023.).

To improve predictive capacity, future research should also consider advanced resampling methods (e.g., SMOTE), explainable AI techniques (e.g., SHAP values for RF and SVM models), and integration of additional contextual data such as traffic flow, weather, and enforcement density. These enhancements would not only improve model accuracy but also strengthen the interpretive foundation necessary for evidence-based road safety interventions.

To conclude, although our models were limited to approximately 65% balanced accuracy, we believe that they answer our research question, suggesting that it is possible to classify the severity of crashes from road, weather, and related variables. This would enable data-driven decision making in terms of road safety measures, allowing organisational bodies to pre-emptively implement appropriate measures in high-risk areas.
